BRFSS Data Profiling

Crystal

Reference codebook: https://www.cdc.gov/brfss/annual_data/2018/pdf/codebook18_llcp-v2-508.pdf

brfss2018 <- read_csv("~/git/dspg20career/src/brfss/brfss2018.csv")%>%
  select(-X1)
data_profiling <- function(df){
summary_table <- tibble(var = names(df),
       variable_type = map(.x = df, .f = function(col) class(x = col)),                 
       num_unique = map_int(.x = df, .f = function(col) length(x = unique(x = col))),
       num_missing = map_int(.x = df, .f = function(col) sum(x = is.na(x = col)))) %>%
  mutate(perc_missing = round(x = 100 * num_missing / nrow(x = .), digits = 2L))

return(summary_table)
}

brfss2018%>%
  data_profiling()%>%
  gt()
var variable_type num_unique num_missing perc_missing
X_STATE numeric 53 0 0.0
age numeric 63 0 0.0
race character 10 1 12.5
income character 10 4394 54925.0
sex character 3 0 0.0
education character 8 34 425.0
veteran character 4 558 6975.0
employment character 10 1236 15450.0

The sample size of BRFSS 2018 is 437436. Calculated variables are: state, age, BMI, income. Self reported variables are: sex, marital status, education level, home rental status, veteran status, employment status, self reported income.

plot_bar(brfss2018)

plot_histogram(brfss2018)

DC

dc <- brfss2018%>%
  filter(X_STATE == 11)  #DC is coded 11

#glimpse(brfss2018)
plot_bar(dc)

plot_histogram(dc)

Veteran/Age

dc_vet <- dc%>%
  filter(veteran %in% c("Yes", "No"))

ggplot(dc_vet, aes(x = age, fill = veteran)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 3) + 
 # aes(colour = veteran) + 
  labs(title = "") + 
  theme(legend.position = "top") + 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2")

Veteran/Race

vet_race <- table(dc_vet$veteran, dc_vet$race)%>%
  as.data.frame()%>%
  rename("veteran" = "Var1", "race" = "Var2")

ggplot(vet_race, aes(x = race, y = Freq))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill = veteran), 
           stat = "identity")+ 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2")+
  facet_wrap(~veteran) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))
